[WNBA](https://www.foxnews.com/category/sports/wnba) star Brittney Griner believes her new documentary about her time imprisoned in Russia compares to the current situation in the United States.

With ICE agents cracking down on immigration in major cities across the country, Griner told [The Hollywood Reporter](https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/politics-news/brittney-griner-documentary-airing-espn-ice-1236486456/#recipient_hashed=a4c5a0935a921bd877acf45ec6309fc2f5c13d8d613bf6dadd003e79c1707e03&recipient_salt=94e4947d540768296bf8b68f757d2a71c9c90edd6de8fd5f0a8cec5e4ab0f96e&utm_medium=email&utm_source=exacttarget&utm_campaign=Breaking%20News&utm_content=660669_01-27-2026&utm_term=12232194?utm_medium=email&utm_source=exacttarget&utm_campaign=1769550513-Breaking+News&utm_content=660669_1-27-2026&utm_id=660669) she hopes her 30 for 30 documentary, which premieres at the 2026 Sundance Film Festival Tuesday night and will air later this year on ESPN, will "shed some light" on what the country could become "if we keep letting this happen.

"Right now, we’re in a very bad place, especially with everything that’s going on in Minnesota and just across our country," Griner told the outlet. "I definitely think people will understand a little bit more now and be able to see some comparisons."

